<paragraph id="470F36E8E963ED52435FFD99CF1676E7" blockId="11.[824,1099,639,663]" box="[824,1099,639,663]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
<heading id="1C478184E963ED52435FFD99CF1676E7" box="[824,1099,639,663]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" reason="4">
FAMILY 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243F9FD99CF1676E7" box="[926,1099,639,663]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">XYLOMYIDAE</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="470F36E8E963ED5542BFFD56C92876D7" blockId="11.[696,1225,688,1738]" lastBlockId="12.[120,649,226,679]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
This is a relatively small family of approximately 143 species as of 2016, comprising four living genera. Two of the living genera of 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5244ECFD15C854775C" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xylomyidae</taxonomicName>
are nearly cosmopolitan, 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED52444BFCF2C9B7773D" authority="Rondani" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52444BFCF2CFD7775C" box="[1068,1162,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya</emphasis>
Rondani
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED524349FCD3C890773D" authority="Walker." authorityName="Walker." box="[814,973,821,845]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED524349FCD3C834773D" box="[814,873,821,845]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Solva</emphasis>
Walker.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243BEFCD3CF9A773D" authority="Lindner" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1949" box="[985,1223,821,845]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243BEFCD3CF3C773D" box="[985,1121,821,845]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Arthropeina</emphasis>
Lindner
</taxonomicName>
contains six neotropical species (Fachin and Amorim, 2014); the monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED52441EFC91C82877C0" authority="Brunetti" authorityName="Brunetti" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Coenomyiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52441EFC91C84D77C0" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Coenomyiodes</emphasis>
Brunetti
</taxonomicName>
is from 
<collectingCountry id="3FA77678E963ED5243B3FC7ECF5377C0" box="[980,1038,920,944]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">India</collectingCountry>
and very poorly known. 
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52437EFC5CC8E177A1" box="[793,956,954,977]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Macroceromyx</emphasis>
Bigot is now synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED52435DFC3CC8CA7782" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" box="[826,919,986,1010]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52435DFC3CC8CA7782" box="[826,919,986,1010]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243AAFC3CCFCD7782" authority="James" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1939" box="[973,1168,986,1010]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Formosolva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243AAFC3CCF177782" box="[973,1098,986,1010]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Formosolva</emphasis>
James
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5242DFFC1DC8EA7063" authority="(Woodley, 2011)" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[696,951,1019,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5242DFFC1DC9AF7063" box="[696,754,1019,1043]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Solva</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED524365FC1DC8F27063" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[770,943,1019,1043]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="417 - 453" refId="ref61606" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2011. A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In F. C. Thompson, I. Brake, and O. Lonsdale (editors), Contributions to the biosystematic database of world Diptera. Myia 12: 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">Woodley, 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The world species were cataloged by 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED52433DFBFACF4A7044" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[858,1047,1052,1076]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="417 - 453" refId="ref61606" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2011. A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In F. C. Thompson, I. Brake, and O. Lonsdale (editors), Contributions to the biosystematic database of world Diptera. Myia 12: 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">Woodley (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, who also discussed relationships of the genera. 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED52443FFBDBCFCE7025" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[1112,1171,1085,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52443FFBDBCFCE7025" box="[1112,1171,1085,1109]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Solva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5242DFFBB8C8627006" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1949" box="[696,831,1118,1142]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5242DFFBB8C8627006" box="[696,831,1118,1142]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
both hold the abdomen elevated and have extensive membrane on tergite 1, and are closely related (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED5243E8FB47CF9870C9" author="Papavero, N. &amp; J. N. Artigas" box="[911,1221,1184,1209]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="101 - 113" refId="ref60108" refString="Papavero, N., and J. N. Artigas. 1991. Phylogeny of the American genera of Solvidae (Xylomyidae) (Diptera), with illustrations of the female spermatheca. Gayana Zoologia 55 (2): 101 - 113." type="journal article" year="1991">Papavero and Artigas, 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED5242DEFB24C83170AA" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[697,876,1218,1242]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="417 - 453" refId="ref61606" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2011. A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In F. C. Thompson, I. Brake, and O. Lonsdale (editors), Contributions to the biosystematic database of world Diptera. Myia 12: 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">Woodley, 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243E3FB24CF7870AA" box="[900,1061,1218,1242]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Coenomyiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243E3FB24CF7870AA" box="[900,1061,1218,1242]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Coenomyiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is possibly a derived species of 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243ECFB05C8B4708B" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" box="[907,1001,1251,1275]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243ECFB05C8B4708B" box="[907,1001,1251,1275]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or a sister group to 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5242DDFAE2C880716C" authority="(Woodley, 2011)" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[698,989,1284,1308]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5242DDFAE2C845716C" box="[698,792,1284,1308]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED524340FAE2C888716C" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[807,981,1284,1308]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="417 - 453" refId="ref61606" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2011. A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In F. C. Thompson, I. Brake, and O. Lonsdale (editors), Contributions to the biosystematic database of world Diptera. Myia 12: 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">Woodley, 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The fossil record of the family is sparse, including a species in Early Cretaceous Lebanese amber, 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED524472FAA0C8C2710F" authority="Grimaldi and Arillo" authorityName="Grimaldi and Arillo" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Cretoxyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azari">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED524472FAA0CF95712E" box="[1045,1224,1350,1374]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Cretoxyla azari</emphasis>
Grimaldi and Arillo
</taxonomicName>
, and an undescribed species possibly in this family preserved in Early Cretaceous Spanish amber (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E963ED52446CFA4FC9AE7192" author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; A. Arillo &amp; J. Cumming &amp; M. Hauser" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="293 - 332" refId="ref57883" refString="Grimaldi, D., A. Arillo, J. Cumming, and M. Hauser. 2011. Brachyceran Diptera (Insecta) in Cretaceous ambers, part IV: significant new orthorrhaphous taxa. Zookeys 148: 293 - 332." type="journal article" year="2011">Grimaldi et al., 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52436DFA2CC8217192" box="[778,892,1482,1506]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED52436DFA2CC82F7192" box="[778,882,1482,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xylomyia</taxonomicName>
?
</emphasis>
(sic: 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243A4FA2CCF7F7192" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[963,1058,1482,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243A4FA2CCF7F7192" box="[963,1058,1482,1506]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED52445FFA2CCF957192" box="[1080,1224,1482,1506]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">shcherbakovi</emphasis>
Mostovski, from the Late Jurassic of 
<collectingCountry id="3FA77678E963ED52440DFA0DC9B57254" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, is just a fragment of a wing whose identity is impossible to assess. Otherwise, all other fossils are from the Eocene: 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED524472F9A8C87B72F7" authority="Melander" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1949" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inornata">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED524472F9A8CF957216" box="[1045,1224,1614,1638]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Solva inornata</emphasis>
Melander
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED524316F989CF9572F7" authority="Cockerell" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1914" box="[881,1224,1647,1671]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moratula">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED524316F989CF1772F7" box="[881,1098,1647,1671]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Xylomya moratula</emphasis>
Cockerell
</taxonomicName>
from Florissant, and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE963ED5243C2F976CF3F72D8" authority="Loew" authorityName="Loew" box="[933,1122,1680,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE963ED5243C2F976CF7D72D8" box="[933,1056,1680,1704]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Solva nana</emphasis>
Loew
</taxonomicName>
in Baltic amber. Thus, the finding of three xylomyids in Burmese amber (described below) significantly adds to the fossil record. The two new genera differ from modern ones by possessing obvious tergal sulci and no thickened node or weak area on the short stem of vein Rs. In all 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE964ED554263FE80C963750E" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[516,574,358,382]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Solva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE964ED554263FE80C963750E" box="[516,574,358,382]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="12">Solva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
I have examined Rs is weakened only; 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE964ED5541BFFE61C90075EF" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1949" box="[472,605,391,415]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE964ED5541BFFE61C90075EF" box="[472,605,391,415]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="12">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has this stem weakened and with a thickened node; 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE964ED55401EFE2FCB857591" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[121,216,457,481]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE964ED55401EFE2FCB857591" box="[121,216,457,481]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="12">Xylomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the membrane surrounding the apex of Rs thickened and yellowed. Unfortunately, none of the fossils are males, so certain genitalic features could not be assessed (e.g., enlarged male cerci, and epandrium with large lateral processes, as is found in 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE964ED5541B5FD88C96D76F6" baseAuthorityName="Woodley" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[466,560,622,646]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Xylomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE964ED5541B5FD88C96D76F6" box="[466,560,622,646]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="12">Xylomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Other differences are noted in the diagnoses, below.
</paragraph>
